{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kent_ver01/data/sn92051227/00415620743/1920102201/0263.xml":{"full_text":"rvvo\nNOT A SERVICE\nMAN ATTHE\nGORE SPEECH\n5 United States Senator Thomas P.\nGore of Oklahoma, who since his\ns -overwhelming defeat for renomina\ntlon because of the indignation he\naroused in home state by his opposi\ntion to the entrance of the United\nStates into the war against Germany,\nand his consistent opposition to patri\notic legislation during the war, reach-\ned Bridgeport last 'night in his head\n1 ,1ong flight eastward from his con\nA stltuents. In company with two other\nj repudiated office seekers from out of\nf 'town, Mr. Gore addressed a meeting\ni last night at Armory Athletic Club\nhall under the auspices of an organi\ni zation calling Itself the Anti-League\nDemocrats. The fact that a check of\nj .the audience failed to disclose the\npresence of a' single service button\nsuggests the character of support to\nwhich the organization appeals.\nIn introducing Senator Gore, the\nchairman praised Kaiser Wilhelm'as\na man who alwsy agreed with his\ncabinet and referred to Senator Gore\n.as a victim of Wilsonian oppression.\nSenator Gore spoke for nearly an\nhour and said that while' \"America\nJ could never hope to have a more\ns brilliant representative in the council\nof the League of. Nations than Presi-\ndent Wilson had been,\" he was op-\nposed to the league.\nEx-Alderman Edward' Coffey' of\nNew Haven complained bitterly that\ni Governor Cox had refused to turn\naside from his campaign to answer a\nletter which Mr. Coffey had sent him.\nHe also denounced Governor Cox for\nStyling the situation in Ireland a\n\"world tragedy\" and promising to\nbring the cause of Irish freedom be-\nfore the League of Nations, contend-\ning that Senator Harding was right\nin his assertion that the Irish ques\nJ tion was a purely domestic one under\nthe league.\nMr. Coffey's chief grievance was\nthe use of green ink in Democratic\ncampaign material.\nModerators For\nThe Election\nModeraors for the coming elec\nJtion were named yesterday by the\n\"Registrars of Voters as follows:\nt H-irst district. Frank L. Wilder, No.\n18 West avenue: Second, John P.\niKemple, No. 376: Warren street:\nT Third, Fred Emeneer, No. 62 King\nI street; Fourth, Michael Barrett, No.\n195 Hanover street; Fifth, first, Wal\nter Chapman, No. 1,282 Iranistan ave\ni nue; Fifth, second, James Martin, No.\n131 Merchant street; Sixth, first, Jo\nseph Kennell, No. 1.655 North ave\nnue;- Sixth, second, Frank J. Clancy,\nNo. 50 Wheeler avenue: Seventh\nRichard S. Swain. No. 306 Golden Hill\nstreet: Eighth, Filander C. Tibbals,\nNo. 115 Whitney avenue; Ninth, first,\n.Harry Spiro, No. 446 Shelton street;\n.Ninth, second. Charles H. Roder, No.\ni 422 James street: Tenth, James L.\nIHearn, No. 135 Beach street: Elev\nfenth. William A. Redden. No. 207\nPembroke street; Twelfth, first,\n'James Donnelly, No. 1,304 Seaview\navenue: Twelfth, second. Thomas Cal\nlahan, No. 4 56 .Wilmot avenue. v\nHayes Healing Honey\nj Stops the Tickle, Heals the Throat and\nCures the Cough. Price 35c. A free\nbox of GROVE'S O-PEN-TRATE\nSALVE for Chest Colds, Head Colds\nand Croup is enclosed with every bot\ntie. Adv.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nOF THE BRIGHTEST\nNew Tork. Oct 22 Business pros\npects are unusually- bright, both in\nthe United States' and abroad, Elbert\nH. Gary, head of the United States\ni. Steel Corporation, declared in an ad\ndress on \"The Situation in France\ni and Belgium\" before the American\nIron and Steel Institute here today.\nJ \"Although this is a time for cour-\nage, composure and caution,\" Mr.\nt Gary said, \"the business skies are.\n5 practically without clouds, as always,\nthere may be showers from time to\n3 lima, but there is nothing in the at\nmosphere to indicate the approach of\ndangerous storms.\n\"If there should be a serious reac\ntion and depression,\" he continued,\n\"which now ceem improbable, it will\nfee the fault of those who are con-\nhected with business operations, or\ni pthers who1 by reason of official posi\ntions improperly interfere, and not\nbecause of .any fundamental deflcien-\ncies in our resources and opportuni-\nties.\n\"Without referring to individual\ncases or lines of general business, 1\nbelieve in many instances prices have\nbeen outrageously high. This obser\nvation applies more especially to mid\ndlemen, so-called, and to smaller\ndepartments of industry. It also in\ncludes employes in certain trades; but\nit does not pertain under present con.\nditions to the masses of workmen.\"\nA Portuguese airship attempting to\nfly from Lisbon to Madeira fell into\nthe sea during a fog. The aviators\nwere saved by the British steamship\nGambia River.\nGrand Jury probe of alleged short\nage in municipal coal account funds\nin Albany has resulted in the indict\nment of. three minor city officials,\nPolice at Milan declared the bomb\nwhich exploded pn the doorstep of\nthe Cavour Hotel Milan, was evident\nly not intended for members of the\nAllied Mission.\nv CURTIS\nPIANO\n$450.00\nNew England made Piano\ni convenient terms.\nM. Steinert Sons Co.,\n915 'Main St.,\nBridgeport, Conn.\nGet' the habit of reading\nTimes Classified Ads!\nI SEND FLOWERS I\nI ALWAYS t\nBridgeport, Conn.,\nFriday, Oct. 22, 120.\nAnother chance\nWomen's beautiful suits and handsome coats,\nregular $50 to $85 sorts $39.50\n'6Vi\nChoice of either\nMore of special\nhome need values.\nFrom two or three hundred, or more, articles of ser\nvice in every home to be chosen at saving here are more\nT f\nexamples i\nOut glass celery trays and bowls and nappies, regular\n$3.25 $2.50.\nRapid egg beaters, regular 25c 19c.\nSalt and pepper shakers,, special at 15c 25e pair.\nSherbet glasses, regular $1.10 dozen 85c.\nEnglish and American teapots of handsome effect,\nregular 60c to $1.75 45c to $1.25.\nDinnersets of 100 pieces, American porcelain, regular\n$30 $19.50.\nCups and saucers in number of good patterns, regular\n$3.50 doz each 25c.